[3] Maryland (Anne Arundel County): cat, human exposure
Date: Mon 10 Jul 2016
Source: The Baltimore Sun [edited]
http://www.baltimoresun.com/ph-ac-cn-rabid-cat-0710-20160710-story.html


The county Health Department is asking to be called by anyone who may have come in contact with a cat, found in Glen Burnie [Anne Arundel County] that has tested positive for rabies.

The grey and black tiger shorthair tabby was found on [Thu 7 Jul 2016] near Hamlen Road in the Munroe Gardens community, according to a Health Department release.

Anyone who had contact with a stray, wild, or unfamiliar cat in that area should immediately call the county Department of Health at 410-222-7256, Monday through Friday from 8 am to 5 pm, and 443-481-3140 after business hours.

Also, anyone whose pet was bitten or scratched by a cat should call County Animal Control at 410-222-8900.

Rabies is spread by the bite or scratch of an infected animal, such as a cat, raccoon, fox, or bat. It is also spread when the infected animal's saliva comes in contact with the eyes, nose, mouth, or open cut of a person or another animal.

Rabies is a potentially fatal disease and preventive treatment through vaccines must be started as soon as possible by anyone who handled or fed the cat.

The Health Department asks county residents to not feed stray or wild animals or leave food dishes outside. Pet owners should also keep their animals' rabies vaccinations current.

[Byline: Gerald Fischman]

